./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-1_20260620T070243Z.log:1839:./reviews/code-review-claude.md:9:### [L2] No SIGINT/SIGTERM handler — lock leaks on interrupt | orchestrator.py:1-1123 | Despite documentation claiming "SEAN Ctrl-C (SIGINT → graceful shutdown)," there is no `signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, ...)` registered anywhere. A `KeyboardInterrupt` during `subprocess.run()` will propagate past the `finally` block in `run()` (line 203) ONLY if no cleanup is done between the exception and the frame unwind. If the interrupt arrives during `_run_state_machine()` or `_run_loop()`, the lock is released in the `finally` block. However, if the interrupt arrives during `subprocess.run()` inside a runner (which is called without a try/except), the exception propagates up to `_run_state_machine()` and then to the `finally` block—so the lock IS released, but there is no partial-state save or checkpoint. Worse: the orchestrator does not set `halt_signal` on SIGINT, so an Observer polling `state()` will never see a halt reason. | Register `signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, lambda s, f: self.halt("SIGINT"))` in `__init__` or at the start of `run()`. Wrap the body of `run()` in a `try: ... finally: self._lock_mgr.release(project_name)` (already done). Additionally save a checkpoint on halt before releasing the lock so resumption is possible.
