./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T064626Z.log:1343:The design fixed the earlier single-fd issue by switching to a per-project `_fds` map. One regression stands out in the proposed `release()` path, so I’m validating its impact against `flock` semantics before writing the review.
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T064626Z.log:1364:The current `release()` design would remove the lock path even when this manager never acquired it. With `flock`, that can break mutual exclusion because another process can then recreate the path and lock a new inode while the original process still holds the old unlinked inode.
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T064626Z.log:1392:I’m writing the review as `REQUEST_CHANGES`. The existing lock tests pass, but the plan still has a correctness hole in ownership-safe release behavior.
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T064626Z.log:1401:     6	  - "prd/tech-design.md:22 and prd/tech-design.md:31-40 track a single self._fd for all locks. A FileLockManager can currently hold multiple project locks, so the design would overwrite the first fd when acquiring a second project and release the wrong descriptor."
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T064626Z.log:1417:+summary: Tests pass, but the source still has the TOCTOU race and the revised release design can break flock mutual exclusion.
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T064626Z.log:1420:+  - "prd/tech-design.md:61-71 unlinks self._lock_path(project) even when self._fds.pop(project, None) returns None, meaning a FileLockManager that does not own the lock can remove another process's lock file. With flock this is unsafe: the original process keeps a lock on the old unlinked inode, while a later acquire can create and lock a new file at the same path, allowing two active holders. release() should only unlink after confirming this manager owns the fd, with fallback ownership checks preserved for non-fcntl mode."
